1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,357
[INTRO]

2
00:00:00,657 --> 00:00:01,371
Hey everyone.

3
00:00:01,671 --> 00:00:04,528
I’ve been obsessed with game audio for years.

4
00:00:04,828 --> 00:00:06,971
The one thing that breaks immersion?

5
00:00:07,271 --> 00:00:08,342
A robot voice.

6
00:00:08,642 --> 00:00:11,500
Or parroting the same line over and over.

7
00:00:11,799 --> 00:00:12,514
Enter Inworld.

8
00:00:12,814 --> 00:00:15,671
They just changed the rules for NPC dialogue.

9
00:00:15,971 --> 00:00:16,328
[HOOK]

10
00:00:16,628 --> 00:00:19,128
They shipped a massive TTS integration update.

11
00:00:19,428 --> 00:00:21,571
I spent the weekend torturing it.

12
00:00:21,871 --> 00:00:22,942
Complex emotions? Check.

13
00:00:23,242 --> 00:00:24,314
Fast quips? Check.

14
00:00:24,614 --> 00:00:27,471
Making an NPC whisper a threat? Weird check.

15
00:00:27,771 --> 00:00:29,199
The result is impressive.

16
00:00:29,499 --> 00:00:31,999
But it comes with a massive asterisk.

17
00:00:32,299 --> 00:00:32,657
[BODY]

18
00:00:32,957 --> 00:00:34,385
Let’s talk architecture first.

19
00:00:34,685 --> 00:00:36,471
Inworld has a character brain.

20
00:00:36,771 --> 00:00:38,557
That brain tracks the conversation.

21
00:00:38,857 --> 00:00:42,071
It knows if the NPC is losing an argument.

22
00:00:42,371 --> 00:00:45,228
It knows if the player is being rude.

23
00:00:45,528 --> 00:00:49,100
When you hit “speak”, the brain sends a data bundle.

24
00:00:49,400 --> 00:00:51,900
Text + Emotion + Intent + Style.

25
00:00:52,200 --> 00:00:54,342
Standard TTS just reads the sentence.

26
00:00:54,642 --> 00:00:56,071
Inworld TTS *performs* it.

27
00:00:56,371 --> 00:00:59,942
This is the single biggest leap in NPC dialogue tech.

28
00:01:00,242 --> 00:01:00,600
[EXAMPLE]

29
00:01:00,900 --> 00:01:02,328
Scenario: A tavern brawl.

30
00:01:02,628 --> 00:01:04,057
NPC: The nervous bartender.

31
00:01:04,357 --> 00:01:05,785
Setup 1: Standard TTS.

32
00:01:06,085 --> 00:01:09,657
Input: “Hey! Take it outside before I call the guards!”

33
00:01:09,957 --> 00:01:11,742
Output: Clean. Slightly annoyed. Flat.

34
00:01:12,042 --> 00:01:13,471
Setup 2: Inworld TTS.

35
00:01:13,771 --> 00:01:16,628
Backstory: Ex-adventurer. Hates violence. Scared of a lawsuit.

36
00:01:16,928 --> 00:01:19,428
Context: The player threw the first punch.

37
00:01:19,728 --> 00:01:22,942
Response: *Voice raises an octave.* “HEY! Knock it off!”

38
00:01:23,242 --> 00:01:25,742
*Voice drops, trembles slightly.* “…Take it outside.”

39
00:01:26,042 --> 00:01:29,257
*Frustrated exhale.* “Before I… before I call the guards.”

40
00:01:29,557 --> 00:01:32,057
It didn’t read the line. It *reacted*.

41
00:01:32,357 --> 00:01:34,500
The TTS engine applied dynamic prosody.

42
00:01:34,799 --> 00:01:36,228
It changed the rhythm.

43
00:01:36,528 --> 00:01:38,314
This is the secret sauce.

44
00:01:38,614 --> 00:01:38,971
[BODY2]

45
00:01:39,271 --> 00:01:40,342
Let’s talk practicalities.

46
00:01:40,642 --> 00:01:42,785
Latency is the killer of conversation.

47
00:01:43,085 --> 00:01:45,228
Lowest latency mode? Sub 500ms. Instant.

48
00:01:45,528 --> 00:01:47,671
High quality mode? A bit heavier.

49
00:01:47,971 --> 00:01:50,114
The real magic is emotional mapping.

50
00:01:50,414 --> 00:01:52,557
You can define parameters. “Anger: High.”

51
00:01:52,857 --> 00:01:55,357
Or you can let the brain decide.

52
00:01:55,657 --> 00:01:59,585
I found letting the brain decide gave the most natural results.

53
00:01:59,885 --> 00:02:02,028
It doesn’t scream every angry line.

54
00:02:02,328 --> 00:02:04,471
It gets quiet. It gets scary.

55
00:02:04,771 --> 00:02:06,199
This is intelligent audio.

56
00:02:06,499 --> 00:02:06,857
[BODY3]

57
00:02:07,157 --> 00:02:08,228
Okay. Opinion time.

58
00:02:08,528 --> 00:02:11,028
Is this the best raw TTS engine?

59
00:02:11,328 --> 00:02:13,828
ElevenLabs still rules for pure voice cloning.

60
00:02:14,128 --> 00:02:16,271
PlayHT still wins for voice variety.

61
00:02:16,571 --> 00:02:20,142
But if you need a character that *lives and breathes*?

62
00:02:20,442 --> 00:02:21,871
The gap is enormous.

63
00:02:22,171 --> 00:02:23,957
Inworld wins by a landslide.

64
00:02:24,257 --> 00:02:26,399
The trade off is ecosystem lock-in.

65
00:02:26,699 --> 00:02:29,199
You cannot buy the voice engine standalone.

66
00:02:29,500 --> 00:02:31,642
You buy the whole character suite.

67
00:02:31,942 --> 00:02:33,728
This is perfect for games.

68
00:02:34,028 --> 00:02:36,528
This is restrictive for animatics or ads.

69
00:02:36,828 --> 00:02:38,257
Know your use case.

70
00:02:38,557 --> 00:02:38,914
[OUTRO]

71
00:02:39,214 --> 00:02:42,785
I believe the next generation of RPGs will use this.

72
00:02:43,085 --> 00:02:46,300
Baldur’s Gate 4? Mix this with a dialogue tree.

73
00:02:46,599 --> 00:02:48,385
Infinite variety. Real emotional payoff.

74
00:02:48,685 --> 00:02:51,542
The tech is mature enough to build on.

75
00:02:51,842 --> 00:02:53,985
I am genuinely excited about this.

76
00:02:54,285 --> 00:02:54,642
[CTA

